{"author":{"id":"b78c39e7b13f90a5827abfba043255fe7a4ede1499df23f110fffe5abfa44adc"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1770048417,"nonce":"+gWjIGK2m5ahejgy3OzWpF7AZaE=","metadata":{"github-id":"I_kwDOQ241x87nqx7m","github-url":"https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/issues/123","origin":"github"},"title":"Add workflow selection guidance for agents (simple vs complex changes)","message":"## Problem\n\nCurrent workflows optimize for complex multi-file changes and multi-agent coordination, but may impose unnecessary overhead for simple fixes. There's no clear guidance on when to use each workflow approach.\n\n**Example**: Fixing a 1-line `.gitignore` issue requires choosing between:\n- Full issue workflow (8 steps: issue → worktree → work plan → draft PR → fix → push → ready → cleanup)\n- Direct branch workflow (5 steps: branch → fix → commit → push → PR)\n\nAgents lack clear criteria for selecting the appropriate workflow based on change complexity.\n\n## Friction Example\n\n**Scenario**: Need to fix `.gitignore` to ignore `layers/` directory (1-line change)\n\n**Current guidance** (from AI_RULES.md): \n- Points to `start-feature.md` which emphasizes GitHub issue workflow\n- Recommends `.agent/scripts/start_issue_work.sh` for all work\n- No fast-path for trivial changes\n\n**Result**: \n- Uncertain whether to create issue first\n- Worktree overhead feels heavy for single-line fix\n- Work plan seems unnecessary for trivial change\n\n## Proposed Solution\n\nAdd **workflow selection guidance** to help agents choose the right approach:\n\n### Fast Path (Option 2): Lightweight Worktree\n\n**Use for:**\n- Single-file changes (\u003c 20 lines)\n- Configuration/documentation fixes\n- No multi-agent coordination needed\n- Low risk of conflicts\n\n**Steps:**\n```bash\n# 1. Create worktree (use issue number if exists, or temporary number)\n.agent/scripts/worktree_create.sh --issue \u003cN\u003e --type workspace\n\n# 2. Make changes, commit, push\ncd .workspace-worktrees/issue-\u003cN\u003e\n# ... edit files ...\ngit add \u003cfiles\u003e\ngit commit -m \"fix: \u003cdescription\u003e\"\ngit push -u origin HEAD\n\n# 3. Create PR\ngh pr create --title \"...\" --body \"...\"\n\n# 4. Clean up\n.agent/scripts/worktree_remove.sh \u003cN\u003e\n```\n\n**Benefits:**\n- ✅ Isolated workspace (safe)\n- ✅ No work plan overhead\n- ✅ Can abandon easily\n- ✅ ~6 steps vs 8\n\n### Full Issue Workflow (Option 1)\n\n**Use for:**\n- Multi-file changes\n- Complex features\n- Work requiring coordination\n- Changes needing design discussion\n\n### Direct Branch (Option 3)\n\n**Use for:**\n- Typo fixes\n- Emergency hotfixes\n- When main workspace is already clean\n\n## Implementation\n\nAdd `.agent/workflows/dev/workflow-selection.md`:\n- Decision tree for choosing workflow\n- Examples of each category\n- When to skip work plans\n\nUpdate `AI_RULES.md`:\n- Link to workflow selection guide\n- Remove implication that all work needs issue-first\n\n## Impact\n\n- ✅ Reduces overhead for simple fixes\n- ✅ Keeps safety of worktrees for most changes\n- ✅ Clearer agent decision-making\n- ✅ Faster iteration on trivial fixes\n\n## Priority\n\n🟡 Medium - Reduces efficiency for common simple-fix scenarios\n\n## Session Evidence\n\nSession: dcd4862f-6c8c-4de5-9645-dce56aae1593\n- Fixed `.gitignore` issue (worktree symlink false positive)\n- 1-line change to `.gitignore` \n- Discussion revealed workflow selection uncertainty\n- No clear guidance on when to use which approach\n\n---\n**🤖 Reported-By**: Copilot CLI Agent (Claude Sonnet 4.5)","files":null}]}